---
/*
 * S11AgentsRecipes.astro — Agents & Recipes section
 *
 * Two-zone layout per Section.astro architecture:
 *   entry slot  — Eyebrow → BlurReveal(h2) → lead
 *   default slot — Agents are bundles (3p) → Context files (3p) →
 *                  Recipes (1p + 3 concepts) → Skills (2p) → UpNextTeaser
 *
 * Background: slate (#161619). Technical mode (azure eyebrow).
 */
import Section from '../components/sections/Section.astro';
import Eyebrow from '../components/content/Eyebrow.astro';
import BlurReveal from '../components/content/BlurReveal.astro';
import UpNextTeaser from '../components/content/UpNextTeaser.astro';
---

<Section id="s11" label="Agents & Recipes" background="slate">
  <Fragment slot="entry">
    <Eyebrow label="AGENTS & RECIPES" />
    <BlurReveal>
      <h2 class="s11__headline">Agents, skills, recipes: each one is built from pieces you have already seen.</h2>
    </BlurReveal>
    <p class="s11__lead">Every feature in this section uses sessions, bundles, and modules. No new kernel support was added. Each feature was assembled from the primitives covered in the sections above.</p>
  </Fragment>

  <div class="s11__body">
    <h3 class="s11__sub">Agents are bundles</h3>
    <p>Agents are bundles. Same file format. Same parser. Same composition, @mentions, and merge rules.</p>
    <p>One difference: the YAML frontmatter key. A bundle uses <em>bundle:</em>. An agent uses <em>meta:</em>. That's it. Everything else (how the file is read, how instructions are parsed, how modules load) is identical.</p>
    <p>The kernel has no concept of 'agents.' It runs sessions with configurations. The naming is a semantic signal for humans: agent files represent complete autonomous entities, bundle files represent configuration fragments.</p>

    <h3 class="s11__sub">Context files</h3>
    <p>A context file is a Markdown document that gets loaded into the AI's working memory at the start of each conversation turn. Context files are what @mentions reference.</p>
    <p>The value of context files is separation of concerns. Instead of cramming every piece of background knowledge into the bundle's instruction body, you put each topic in its own file.</p>
    <p>Context files are also composable. A context file can contain @mentions of its own, referencing other context files, up to three levels deep.</p>

    <h3 class="s11__sub">Recipes</h3>
    <p>Sometimes a task is too complex for a single agent conversation. It involves multiple steps, each requiring different capabilities, where the output of one step feeds into the next. Recipes handle this.</p>
    <div class="s11__concepts">
      <div class="s11__concept">
        <span class="s11__concept-label">Sequential execution</span>
        <p>A recipe is a YAML file that defines a sequence of steps. Each step runs its own agent session with its own bundle, tools, and instructions. Output from step N becomes input to step N+1.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="s11__concept">
        <span class="s11__concept-label">Approval gates</span>
        <p>Points in the sequence where execution pauses and waits for a human decision. Between steps, a person can review the current output before the system continues.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="s11__concept">
        <span class="s11__concept-label">Resumability</span>
        <p>Each step creates a checkpoint. If something fails at step four of a seven-step recipe, you don't need to start over from step one. Resume from the last successful checkpoint.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="s11__sub">Skills</h3>
    <p>An agent can use tools and delegate to other agents, but sometimes what it needs is knowledge: coding standards for a specific framework, deployment procedures for a particular cloud provider, the team's naming conventions. Skills fill this role.</p>
    <p>The loading follows a three-level progressive disclosure pattern. Level one is metadata: the skill's name and a one-line description, always visible. Level two is the full body content, loaded only when the agent decides the skill is relevant. Level three is companion files that the skill can reference but that stay on disk until explicitly read.</p>
  </div>
  <UpNextTeaser nextSection="Complete Picture" teaser="Each layer depends only on the one below it." />
</Section>

<style>
  /* —— Entry: headline ————————————————————————————————————————————————————— */
  .s11__headline {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: var(--text-h2);
    font-weight: 600;
    line-height: var(--leading-tight);
    letter-spacing: var(--tracking-tight);
    color: var(--text-primary);
    max-width: 20ch;
    margin: 0;
  }

  /* —— Entry: lead ————————————————————————————————————————————————————————— */
  .s11__lead {
    font-size: clamp(1.125rem, 1.2vw, 1.25rem);
    line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
    color: var(--text-body);
    max-width: 55ch;
    margin: var(--space-4) 0 0;
  }

  .s11__lead em {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }

  /* —— Body ————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————— */
  .s11__body {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-3);
    color: var(--text-body);
    max-width: 60ch;
  }

  .s11__body p {
    line-height: var(--leading-normal);
  }

  .s11__body em {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }

  /* —— Sub-headings ————————————————————————————————————————————————————————— */
  .s11__sub {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: var(--text-body);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--text-primary);
    margin: var(--space-2) 0 0;
    line-height: var(--leading-normal);
  }

  /* —— Recipe concepts ————————————————————————————————————————————————————— */
  .s11__concepts {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-3);
  }

  .s11__concept {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-1);
  }

  .s11__concept-label {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--text-small);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--accent);
    letter-spacing: 0.02em;
  }

  .s11__concept p {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: var(--text-small);
    line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
  }
</style>
